title: For Sale:  Sig 556 DMR
postcontent:
Lightly used Sig 556 DMR with 200 rounds through it.

Gorgeous, and VERY accurate Sig 556 piston driven 21" 5.56 / .223 rifle.  I attached a 1/4" by 1/2" 3 shot group from 100yds.  That is how accurate this gun is.

This is a rare rifle that was only imported by Sig for 2 years.  The design was then changed to a shorter 18" and I still haven't seen one of the new ones for sale.

For those that don't know what DMR is.  DMR stands for Designated Marksman Rifle.  The Designated Marksman program was a small unit sniper designation that the USMC gave to accurate infantrymen.  They were given upgraded optics and a longer barrel than the standard 16" M4 that was issued at the time.  DMR guns were required to use standard AR magazines with 5.56 chambers, and have increased accuracy over the standard M4.  It was very successful and continues to this day.

Came from the factory with:
Magpul PRS (Precision Rifle Sniper) buttstock.
Flat top picatinny with quad rail foregrip.
Adjustable 2 Stage trigger (VERY LIGHT from factory!)
Harris Bipod and Bipod mount
21" Forged partially free floated Bull Barrel with target crown.
Sig Sauer adjustable piston system.


I can also include Nikon M223 3-12x scope on quick release burris picatinny mount, MBUS sights, and Grip Pod for additional.

Trade for Stag 3g, DPMS 3g1, or STi Competition rifle will be considered.  As well, trade for a high end 1911 will be considered as well.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Colt .22 Revolver (Nickle)
postcontent:
Here is a rare Colt Official Police Revolver in .22 lr caliber. These guns were made for about 30 years or so, (from around 1930-1969) and almost all of them were in .38 special.
 Only about 47K were made in this caliber, and were often used as police training pistols for target practice in conjunction with their .38s.
 Most all of the Colt Official Police .22s came with the blued finish, and usually sell for in the $700 plus range, with the scarce original nickled versions going for around $1200. 
 This one has been refinished, so it is priced accordingly. It is a wonderful 'shooter'- & is mechanically very tight, cheap to shoot, & darned accurate. Barrel length is 6". Bore is perfect.
 This gun was made in 1953, and wears the original Colt grips. 
  If you want a rare Colt .22 in the scarce Nickle finish, that is a great shooter/plinker with old school American quality & accuracy....You'll love this Vintage Colt!
 This is a predecessor to the Python with smooth action & timing, and overbuilt for a .22....It'll be 60 yrs. old next year and is barely broken in.
 Pics on request, and trades are welcome too.

*  Leupold Mark AR 3-9x40 Tactical MIL (TMD) Reticle
	- Includes rings, lens protector, and all user manuals & additional info booklets 
*  Harris 1A2 spring adjustable bipod
*  Two 20 round factory magazines
*  Solid quality rifle case
*  All DPMS original paperwork and user manuals included.


==== ABOUT ====
This is an AR-10 that DPMS designed as a base-model .308 semi-automatic precision match rifle to start your build from.  It is just as it was when it left the factory as no modifications have been made. Exactly 64 rounds have been fired from this rifle so it still remains in excellent DPMS manufactured out-of-the-box condition.

The rifle performed much better than I had expected a semi-automatic match rifle to  perform.  With precise and consistent loads, it throws sub-MOA groups at 300 yards regularly.  Unfortunately, the ergonomics just simply didn't gel with my body shape, so it was hard for me to find a relaxed natural and neutral position.  This made things awkward for me at 700-1,000 yard distances.  For me personally, a bolt-action platform better suits my needs and shooting preferences.

I do still like this rifle and am in no big rush to part with it; however, I would like to find it a home that might fit the furniture more comfortably and/or be better able to take full advantage of its performance potential than me. It would allow me to more quickly start moving forward with a bolt rifle.

Anyway, I wanted to see what the interest level is out here and to tell any of you serious shoppers looking to build a semi-auto .308 precision rifle to feel free contact me anytime, I'd be happy to answer any questions you might have.  Thanks!


==== ADDITIONAL NOTES ====
I live in Lake Jackson TX (50 miles south of Houston) and if anyone wants to come down to check the rifle out first, just let me know. I'm happy to oblige and happy to make any sale in person. Unfortunately, my transportation options are limited right now.
